<div class="wrap">
  <section class="hero">
    <span class="eyebrow">About</span>
    <h1>Why I built this</h1>
    <p class="thesis">I'm <b>Alan Lacroix</b>. I was born in Mexico City and moved to the United States when I was young. I'm building a business in Mexico now, and I go home often — and somewhere along the way I realized I'd lost touch with what was actually happening there: the economy, the politics, the mood of the place. This site is how I got it back.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>What it is</h2>
    <p>The Mexico Brief pulls Mexico's real numbers straight from the source — Banxico, INEGI, Hacienda, and the U.S. agencies that track the relationship — every figure dated and one tap from where it came from. But numbers alone don't tell you what's going on. So I pair them with the developments that move them: the decisions, the decrees, the deals, each linked to its own report.</p>
    <p>Facts first, with the news that gives them meaning — not the other way around. I'm still working out the best way to do that, and it will keep changing.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>How it started</h2>
    <p>It began as a private tool, just for me — a way to stay current without wading through a dozen government portals in Spanish. Then family and friends started asking me to send it to them. So I opened it up. It's free, and I intend to keep it that way.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>The weekly brief</h2>
    <p>Once a week I write a longer read: the key areas worth your attention across Mexico's economy, politics, and markets, compiled and explained in one place. It's built for investors, executives, and anyone with a real stake in the country and the region. <a class="inline" href="/weekly.html">See a recent issue and subscribe &rarr;</a></p>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>A few things I hold to</h2>
    <ul class="rules">
      <li>Every figure links to the official source it came from, with the date it was published.</li>
      <li>Every number comes from a named, public, first-party institution — all of them listed on the <a class="inline" href="/sources.html">Sources</a> page.</li>
      <li>When a feed goes quiet, its last value stays up, marked with the date it stopped.</li>
      <li>The news is here to explain the numbers, not replace them. Nothing on this site is investment advice, and I have no affiliation with any government or party.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="blk">
    <h2>I'm still building this</h2>
    <p>I'm not done, and I don't think I ever will be. I'm always looking for new first-party sources, better data feeds, and clearer ways to frame what's happening. If you know a source I'm missing, spot an error, or have a way to make this more useful — I genuinely want to hear it.</p>
    <p>Reach me at <a class="inline" href="mailto:alanlacroix94@gmail.com">alanlacroix94@gmail.com</a>.</p>
  </section>
